This is a classic ForgeGradle dependency resolution issue, not a problem with your code. Here's what's happening and how to fix it:

The Problem

ForgeGradle is trying to download a mapped version of Forge (1.21.11-61.0.2) but can't find it on the servers. This usually happens because:

The Forge version is very new - Maven artifacts might not be fully propagated yet
Network/cache issues - ForgeGradle's dependency cache is corrupted
ForgeGradle version mismatch - Your build system might need updating
Immediate Solutions (Try in Order)

1. Force Refresh & Clean (Most Likely Fix)

bash
# Windows
gradlew --refresh-dependencies clean

# Linux/Mac
./gradlew --refresh-dependencies clean
If that doesn't work, try the nuclear option:

bash
# Delete Gradle cache
rm -rf ~/.gradle/caches/forge_gradle/
# Then try building again
./gradlew clean build
2. Check Forge Version Availability

Visit: https://files.minecraftforge.net/net/minecraftforge/forge/
Check if 1.21.11-61.0.2 is actually listed. If it's not, you may need to:

Use a slightly older Forge version that's stable
Or wait for the artifacts to fully deploy
3. Update ForgeGradle

In your build.gradle, update the ForgeGradle version:

gradle
plugins {
    id 'net.minecraftforge.gradle' version '[6.0.24,)' // Try this version
    // or
    id 'net.minecraftforge.gradle' version '6.0.+' // Latest in 6.0.x
}
4. Use a Different Forge Version (Quick Workaround)

If you need to build NOW, temporarily use a slightly older version in gradle.properties:

properties
# Try this instead
minecraft_version=1.21.11
forge_version=61.0.1  # One version older
# or
forge_version=61.0.0  # Two versions older
Long-term Recommendations

For Development:

bash
# Use the IDE integration
./gradlew genIntellijRuns  # For IntelliJ
# or
./gradlew eclipse          # For Eclipse
Then build and run from your IDE, which often handles dependency resolution better.

Build System Health Check:

Check your internet connection - ForgeGradle needs to download ~100MB of dependencies
Disable VPN/proxy if you have one
Check disk space - You need at least 2GB free for Gradle cache

Since you have Java 21 installed, and because Forge 1.21.11 requires Java 21, the most direct solution is to force your project to use Java 21. Here’s how:

🔧 Solution 1: Set JAVA_HOME for This Project (Recommended)

Open a terminal in your project folder and set the Java version for the current session, then update Gradle:

bash
# This command finds the path to Java 21 on your Mac
export JAVA_HOME=$(/usr/libexec/java_home -v 21)

# Verify it worked
java --version  # Should now show "version 21"

# Now the wrapper update command will work
./gradlew wrapper --gradle-version=8.14.1 --distribution-type=bin
⚠️ Why This Works for Forge: Minecraft Forge 1.21.11 is compiled and tested with Java 21. Using Java 25 can cause unexpected compatibility issues, even if you get the build running. Setting the project to Java 21 matches the official toolchain.
🛠️ Solution 2: Manually Edit the Wrapper (If Needed)

If Solution 1 doesn't work, you can manually edit the Gradle wrapper configuration file:

Open the file gradle/wrapper/gradle-wrapper.properties in your project.
Change the distributionUrl line to:

text
distributionUrl=https\://services.gradle.org/distributions/gradle-8.14.1-bin.zip
Save the file.
Then run ./gradlew clean build. This will force the script to download the new, compatible Gradle version.
📋 Permanent Project Configuration

To avoid setting JAVA_HOME every time, add this to your project's gradle.properties file (create it if it doesn't exist):

text
org.gradle.java.home=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-21.jdk/Contents/Home
You can find the exact path for your Java 21 installation by running:

Yes, you can and should uninstall Java 25. Minecraft Forge 1.21.11 is only compatible with Java 21. Using Java 25 is the direct cause of the Unsupported class file major version 69 error.

Here’s how to uninstall Java 25 on your Mac, depending on how you installed it. Always verify Java 21 is installed first.

Step 1: Verify You Have Java 21

Check which Java versions are recognized by your system. This confirms Java 21 is ready as a fallback.

bash
/usr/libexec/java_home -V
You should see an entry for Java SE 21 (or similar) with its exact path.

Step 2: Uninstall Java 25

If you installed it via the official Oracle installer:

Navigate to Macintosh HD/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/ in Finder.
Look for a folder named jdk-25.jdk (or similar, containing "25").
Move this entire folder to the Trash.
Empty the Trash.
Also delete the symbolic link for version 25 (optional but clean):

bash
sudo rm /usr/bin/java25  # Only if this specific link exists
If you installed it via Homebrew:

This is the cleanest method.

bash
# List installed Java versions
brew list --formula | grep openjdk

# Uninstall Java 25 (the formula name might vary)
brew uninstall openjdk@25
# or if it's just called 'openjdk'
brew uninstall --cask oracle-jdk  # If you used the cask version
Step 3: Final Verification

After uninstalling, close and reopen your terminal, then run:

bash
java --version
The output must show version 21. If it still shows version 25, your system path needs adjustment.

Next Steps After Uninstalling

Once only Java 21 is active:

Try running the build again: ./gradlew clean build

📊 Understanding the Problem

These errors are breaking changes in the Minecraft Forge API between versions. Your project folder is named reignofnether-1.20.1-dev, strongly suggesting the codebase is for Minecraft 1.20.1. Building it for 1.21.11 will require updating every single one of these API calls. Here are the key changes shown in your errors:

Old API (e.g., 1.20.1)	New API in 1.21.11	Example in Your Code
new ResourceLocation(...)	ResourceLocation.fromNamespaceAndPath(...)	Your code uses the new method correctly!
player.sendMessage(...)	player.sendSystemMessage(...)	Your code has the new method, but it's being called with the wrong argument type.
Various Entity Classes (Horse, Panda, etc.)	Renamed or moved packages	Classes like Horse no longer exist in the same place.
Tag method returns	Changed from direct type to Optional<T>	ptag.getString("name") now returns Optional<String>, not String.
✅ The Solution: Downgrade Your Build Target to 1.20.1

Given the sheer number of errors (over 5,700) and that your folder and codebase are clearly for 1.20.1, the only practical fix is to reconfigure your project to build for Minecraft 1.20.1. This will make the Forge API match your source code.

Updating your mod to Minecraft Forge 1.21.11 is a significant undertaking because the game introduced major API changes that break existing code. Your compilation errors show your mod's code is still using the old API from 1.20.1.

🔄 Key Breaking Changes You Need to Fix

Based on the official release notes for the new modding environment, here are the primary changes you must make in your source code:

What Changed in 1.21.11	What Your Code Likely Uses (1.20.1)	Impact on Your Mod
ResourceLocation is renamed to Identifier	ResourceLocation	This is likely causing the "cannot find symbol: variable ResourceLocation" errors for all your building registrations and texture paths.
Tag data accessors now return Optional<T>	Direct types (e.g., String, int)	This is causing your RTSPlayerSaveData errors, where getString("name") now returns Optional<String>.
Entity class names and packages have changed (e.g., Horse, Panda)	Old class names (e.g., net.minecraft.world.entity.animal.horse.Horse)	This is causing the "cannot find symbol" errors for Horse, Panda, and other mobs in PortraitRendererModifiers.java.
DistExecutor and TickEvent.Phase are deprecated/removed	Older Forge event system	This causes warnings and errors in PlayerClientboundPacket.java and PlayerClientEvents.java.
🛠️ How to Port Your Code

Porting involves systematically updating these API calls across your entire project. The official recommendation is to use a comparative approach:

Set Up a Reference: Keep your current 1.20.1 project open. In your new 1.21.11 workspace, find a function call that doesn't compile.
Find the Fix: Look at the same function in your 1.20.1 code, then find where it's used in the official Minecraft 1.21.11 source code (which your dev environment should have attached). Compare how the vanilla code was updated and apply the same changes to your mod.
Use Find & Replace: For widespread, mechanical changes like ResourceLocation → Identifier, a project-wide find-and-replace in your IDE is the most efficient first step.
Consult Detailed Guides: The changes above are just the start. For a complete list, consult the official Porting Primer mentioned in the NeoForge notes. This document will cover other changes like updates to the RenderType and BakedQuad systems.
📁 Ensure Your Environment is Ready

Before diving into the code, double-check your project setup:

gradle.properties: Confirm the versions are set correctly (e.g., minecraft_version=1.21.11 and forge_version=61.0.2).
Clean Caches: Run ./gradlew clean and consider deleting the ~/.gradle/caches/forge_gradle/ folder to avoid corrupted download issues.

Upgrading from 1.20.1 to 1.21.11 requires a complete rewrite of large portions of a mod due to fundamental changes in how Minecraft's engine works. This isn't just about adding new features—it's about updating your code to a new architecture.

Here are the key areas where the Java API has fundamentally changed, which directly explains the thousands of errors you're seeing:

🎨 1. Complete Rendering System Overhaul

The graphics pipeline was largely rebuilt. The EntityRenderer system, which is at the core of your NecromancerProjectileRenderer and ThrowableTntRenderer errors, was modernized.

Single Type Parameter: The EntityRenderer class now takes only one type parameter (e.g., EntityRenderer<YourEntity>), not two. This is why you see "type argument NecromancerProjectile is not within bounds of type-variable T".
Vertex System Rewritten: The entire vertex consumer system was redesigned. Methods like endVertex() were removed, and the flow for building and drawing vertices changed significantly. This impacts almost all custom models and renderers.
GUI Rendering Changed: The system for rendering screens and GUI elements was split into "prepare" and "render" phases with a new state-based system, affecting any custom UI.
💾 2. Saved Data and NBT (Data Storage) Modernization

The system for saving custom data (used by your BuildingSaveData, CustomBuildingSaveData, etc.) was updated for safety and consistency.

New SavedData Factory: The SavedDataType and its Builder class were replaced with SavedData.Factory. This is the source of the "cannot find symbol... Builder" error.
Optional-Based NBT API: Methods like CompoundTag.getCompound("key") now return an Optional<CompoundTag>. You must handle the optional result (e.g., with .orElse(new CompoundTag())), which is why you see "Optional<CompoundTag> cannot be converted to CompoundTag".
Registry Access Changes: Reading a BlockState from NBT now requires a HolderLookup.Provider, and methods like BuiltInRegistries.BLOCK.asLookup() no longer exist.
🧭 3. Resource Location and Path Changes

Identifiers for game objects are now handled more strictly.

Private Constructor: The ResourceLocation constructor is now private. You must use static factory methods like ResourceLocation.parse(String) or ResourceLocation.withDefaultNamespace(String) instead.
Singular Data Pack Paths: Folder names in data packs are now singular (e.g., tags/block instead of tags/blocks).
📣 4. Player Messaging

The method for sending messages to players was renamed for clarity between client and server.

player.sendSystemMessage(Component) became player.displayClientMessage(Component, boolean).
🔧 Other Core Changes

Enchantments as Data: Enchantments are now data-driven registry objects, moving away from hardcoded classes.
Holders for Registries: Many registry objects (like Enchantment, Block) are now wrapped in Holder objects for safer referencing.
🧭 How to Tackle This Migration

Fixing this is a major project. You should approach it systematically:

Update Your Foundation: First, correct your gradle.properties or build.gradle to target 1.21.11 and ensure Forge/NeoForge is set to a compatible version (like 61.0.2). You cannot compile 1.20.1 code for 1.21.11.
Fix in Order of Dependency:

Start with SavedData classes: Fix the factory pattern. This is a consistent change across many files.
Update NBT Handling: Change all .getCompound(), .getList(), .getInt() calls to handle Optional returns.
Fix Renderers: Update all EntityRenderer classes to the new single-parameter type and adapt to the new vertex system.
Fix Messaging: Do a global find/replace for sendSystemMessage.
Use Official Resources: The NeoForged Migration Primer is an essential guide. Also, check the official Forge or NeoForge Discord communities for help.

Listing every single change from 1.20.1 to 1.21.11 is a massive undertaking, but you are facing a large number of critical, breaking changes that affect almost every part of a mod. The table below summarizes the major categories of API changes and their direct fixes based on your error logs and official information.

API Category	What Changed (1.20.1 → 1.21.11)	How to Fix (Example)	Why Your Code Broke
Saved Data	SavedDataType.Builder class was removed. The entire API was replaced with SavedData.Factory.	Old: new SavedDataType<>(new SavedDataType.Builder<>(...))
New: new SavedData.Factory<>(..., null)	Your code uses the old Builder pattern, which no longer exists.
NBT (Data Storage)	All getter methods like .getCompound(), .getList(), and .getInt() now return Optional<T> instead of the raw type.	Old: CompoundTag tag = nbt.getCompound("key");
New: CompoundTag tag = nbt.getCompound("key").orElse(new CompoundTag());	The compiler sees you trying to assign an Optional<CompoundTag> to a CompoundTag variable, which is a type mismatch.
Resource Locations	The ResourceLocation constructor is now private. You must use static factory methods.	Old: new ResourceLocation("modid:path")
New: ResourceLocation.fromNamespaceAndPath("modid", "path")	Calling a private constructor from your code is not allowed.
Game Rules	Game rules were refactored to use the Registry system. Mods must now use a new GameRuleBuilder API to create and register custom rules.	Create rules via GameRuleBuilder.forBoolean(true).buildAndRegister(...).	The old way of creating and accessing game rules has been replaced.
Entity Renderers	The EntityRenderer class now takes only one type parameter (EntityRenderer<YourEntity>), not two. The rendering flow and methods were overhauled.	Change class signature from extends EntityRenderer<T, S> to extends EntityRenderer<T>. Update the render method to match the new single-parameter parent class.	Your renderer classes are extending an old class signature that no longer exists.
Registry Keys (Items/Blocks)	You must now explicitly set a RegistryKey in the settings for every Block and Item.	.registryKey(RegistryKey.of(RegistryKeys.ITEM, id))	Blocks and items without a defined registry key will cause crashes like "Block id not set".
Player Messaging	player.sendSystemMessage(Component) was renamed to clarify client/server-side use.	Old: player.sendSystemMessage(...)
New: player.displayClientMessage(..., false)	The method sendSystemMessage simply does not exist in the newer API.
🔄 Why These Changes Feel Massive

The jump to 1.21.11 isn't just about new features like Nautiluses and Spears. As explained in the official Fabric blog, this version is a major technical pivot: it is the last obfuscated version of Minecraft. The development team has been preparing for this by modernizing core systems (like game rules and data), which is why so many foundational APIs you rely on have been rewritten at once.

🛠 What You Should Do Next

You cannot compile your 1.20.1 code against the 1.21.11 libraries. To proceed, you need to:

Systematically Fix by Category: Use the table above. Pick one category (e.g., Saved Data), fix all occurrences in your project, and then move to the next (e.g., NBT handling).
Update Your Mappings: If you're using Fabric, you should start migrating from Yarn to Mojang's official mappings, as support for Yarn will end after 1.21.11.
Consult Official Guides: The NeoForged Migration Primer and the official Fabric Wiki are essential for detailed migration steps.

I see you've made some progress (the SavedData.Factory error is now "cannot find symbol" instead of "Builder not found"), but many core breaking changes remain. The path forward is to tackle these errors systematically, category by category. Here is a practical plan and specific code fixes for the most critical errors in your log.

🎯 The Plan: Fix Categories in This Order

The errors you face fall into distinct groups. Tackle them one at a time, fixing all occurrences of an issue before moving to the next. This is far more efficient than fixing files one by one.

Entity Renderers & Models (Most critical; blocks all rendering)
NBT & Optional Handling (Affects all data saving/loading)
Missing Imports & Simple Renames (Quick, widespread fixes)
API-Specific Changes (Particles, Game Rules, etc.)
1. Fixing Entity Renderers & Models

This is the biggest breaking change. The EntityRenderer and EntityModel class hierarchies were completely redesigned in 1.21.

Problem:
Your ThrowableTntRenderer and NecromancerProjectileRenderer are trying to extend an old version of EntityRenderer that no longer exists.

Solution:
You must update the class signature and the render method. For example, your ThrowableTntRenderer should look something like this:

java
public class ThrowableTntRenderer extends EntityRenderer<ThrowableTntProjectile> {
    // Your texture and constructor here...

    @Override
    public void render(ThrowableTntProjectile entity, float yaw, float partialTick, PoseStack poseStack, MultiBufferSource buffer, int packedLight) {
        // Your rendering logic goes here.
        // You can NO LONGER call super.render().
        // The old parent method with that signature is gone.
    }

    @Override
    public ResourceLocation getTextureLocation(ThrowableTntProjectile entity) {
        return TEXTURE_LOCATION;
    }
}
Key Changes:

extends EntityRenderer<YourEntity> (only one type parameter).
The render method's signature is different. Do not call super.render().
You must implement getTextureLocation.
For Models (EntityModel):
The same principle applies. The EntityModel class now also takes only one type parameter, and the renderToBuffer method signature has changed. You will need to update NecromancerProjectileModel and ThrownMaceModel similarly.

2. Fixing NBT (Data) Optional Handling

Problem:
Methods like .getCompound(), .getList(), and .getInt() now return Optional<T>. You cannot assign an Optional<CompoundTag> directly to a CompoundTag variable.

Solution & Examples:
You must "unwrap" the optional, usually by providing a default value.

java
// OLD: CompoundTag tag = nbt.getCompound("key");
// NEW:
CompoundTag tag = nbt.getCompound("key").orElse(new CompoundTag());

// OLD: ListTag list = nbt.getList("list", 10);
// NEW:
ListTag list = nbt.getList("list").orElse(new ListTag()); // Note: No more 'tag type' parameter

// OLD: int x = blockPosNbt.getInt(0);
// NEW:
int x = blockPosNbt.getInt(0).orElse(0);
Apply this fix everywhere you see "incompatible types: Optional<...> cannot be converted to ...".

3. Fixing Imports & Simple Renames

Many classes moved packages or were renamed. Your IDE should help you with the correct imports. Common ones from your log:

Missing Entity Imports: Horse, Panda, IronGolem, etc. In 1.21, they are typically under net.minecraft.world.entity.animal.* or net.minecraft.world.entity.animal.horse.*.
RenderType: Ensure you have import net.minecraft.client.renderer.RenderType;.
MobSpawnType: Ensure you have import net.minecraft.world.entity.MobSpawnType;.
4. Specific API Fixes

Particles: ParticleTypes.ENTITY_EFFECT is a ParticleType, not a ParticleOptions. You need to create a ColorParticleOption.

java
// OLD: level.addParticle(ParticleTypes.ENTITY_EFFECT, ...);
// NEW:
int color = 0xFF0000; // Example red color
ColorParticleOption particle = new ColorParticleOption(ParticleTypes.ENTITY_EFFECT, color);
level.addParticle(particle, bp.getX(), bp.getY() + 1, bp.getZ(), d0, d1, d2);
Player Messaging: You're on the right track with displayClientMessage, but you're missing the required second boolean parameter.

java
// OLD: player.sendSystemMessage(Component.literal("msg"));
// NEW: (second param: true for action bar, false for chat)
player.displayClientMessage(Component.literal("msg"), false);
Fixing this is a major undertaking, but by isolating and attacking these error categories one by one, you will make steady, measurable progress. The entity rendering and NBT changes will be the most labor-intensive but also the most critical.

For mod developers, the changes between Minecraft 1.21/1.21.1 and 1.21.11 are primarily technical API updates, not a complete rewrite like the earlier 1.20 → 1.21 jump. However, this version is significant as it marks the last version of Minecraft that is obfuscated, which will fundamentally change how the modding toolchain works in the very near future.

The table below summarizes the key modder-facing API changes introduced in 1.21.11 compared to the 1.21 base.

Change Category	What's New / Changed in 1.21.11	Impact / Notes
Core Naming & Tools	ResourceLocation is renamed to Identifier.	A mechanical but widespread find-and-replace change.
Game Rules are refactored to use the registry system. A new GameRuleBuilder API is the standard.	Custom game rules must now be created and registered with the new builder pattern.
Rendering System	The BakedQuad class has been rewritten. It no longer stores data in an opaque int[] but uses explicit fields for vertex positions and UVs, making it easier to understand and work with.	Models and custom rendering code using BakedQuad directly will need updating.
Vanilla RenderType constants are now located in the RenderTypes class.	A simple import change.
Fabric-Specific Changes	World Render Events were reintroduced into the Fabric API.	Fabric mods that need world render hooks can now port this functionality.
New opt-in Packet Splitter API for sending large packets.	Enables new networking patterns for complex data.
Biome Modification API updated to support the new Environment Attributes system.	Allows mods to modify biome temperature, humidity, etc.
Nullability Annotations	Minecraft and NeoForge have switched to JSpecify's @Nullable annotations.	A change for mods that heavily use or check for null values; imports need updating.
🚨 Critical Context for All Modders: The End of Obfuscation

While not a direct API change, the most important news for 1.21.11 is its status as the final obfuscated version of Minecraft. The next version (which will start the new 26.x naming scheme) will be unobfuscated.

This has major implications:

For Fabric/Yarn Users: Yarn and Intermediary mappings will not be updated past 1.21.11. You should begin migrating your mods to Mojang's official mappings as soon as possible to prepare for future versions.
For NeoForge/Forge Users: The change is less dramatic since these loaders already removed obfuscation from their toolchains. However, you will gain access to official parameter names.
🔍 Relating This to Your Migration from 1.20.1

The changes listed above are in addition to the massive API overhaul you've already been tackling, which happened in the jump from 1.20.1 to 1.21. That earlier transition included the data-driven enchantment system, the vertex rendering rewrite, the singular data pack paths (e.g., tags/block), and the private Identifier/ResourceLocation constructor.

In short: Your errors are a mix of:

Fundamental 1.20 → 1.21 API breaks (entity renderers, NBT optionals, SavedData).
Specific 1.21 → 1.21.11 tweaks (like the ResourceLocation to Identifier rename).
The foundational shift to preparing for an unobfuscated Minecraft.
Your strategy of fixing one error category at a time remains the most effective approach.

🔧 Detailed Fixes for Each Pattern

1. Fixing Command Permissions

In your CommandsServerEvents.java, replace the old hasPermission method.

java
// OLD (1.20.1)
.requires(source -> source.hasPermission(2))

// NEW (1.21.11)
.requires(source -> source.hasPermissionLevel(2))
This change is part of the API refactoring in 1.21.11.

2. Handling Optional Returns from Registries

Many of your "Optional<Reference<T>> cannot be converted to T" errors appear in conditional expressions (the ternary operator ?:). The fix is to explicitly unwrap the Optional.

java
// Example for line 370 in CommandsServerEvents.java
// OLD (Broken):
Building building = location == null ? null : ReignOfNetherRegistries.BUILDING.get(location);

// NEW (Fixed):
Building building = location == null ? null : ReignOfNetherRegistries.BUILDING.get(location).orElse(null);
Apply this pattern to every line that tries to assign a value from .get() on your ReignOfNetherRegistries.

3. Fixing Individual Method Calls

Several specific APIs have changed. Here are the key fixes:

Projectile Methods (setItem, shootFromRotation): These methods were likely removed or their signatures changed. You will need to check the 1.21.11 documentation for ThrownHeroExperienceBottle and ThrowableTntProjectile to find the correct way to initialize and launch them. The error that they "cannot be converted to Entity" for addFreshEntity() suggests their inheritance hierarchy may also have changed.
RenderType: The constants have moved. Ensure you have the correct import: import net.minecraft.client.renderer.RenderType;.
InteractionResultHolder: This class still exists. Ensure you have the correct import: import net.minecraft.world.InteractionResultHolder;.
Private Field Access (isClientSide): The isClientSide field on Level is now private. Use the public getter method: pLevel.isClientSide().
Event Methods (getServer(), getEntity()): The methods on events like ServerTickEvent and PlayerTickEvent have been renamed or removed. Check the NeoForge or Fabric documentation for the correct 1.21.11 event API.
Missing Imports (MobSpawnType): Add the import: import net.minecraft.world.entity.MobSpawnType;.

I've read and analyzed all three shared conversation links. The core issue appears to be your ongoing effort to port the "Reign of Nether" Minecraft mod from 1.20.1 to the latest 1.21.1 version, which is encountering massive compilation errors due to major API changes.

Here is a summary connecting all the information:

1. Current Compilation Crisis (Link 1 & 3)

The error logs show the mod is in a severe state of incompatibility with Minecraft 1.21.1. The error count increasing from 4077 to 4099 indicates that some fixes may have introduced new issues or exposed deeper API mismatches. The errors are widespread and systemic:

Rendering System: Complete breakdown of the EntityRenderer system. The inheritance structure (extends EntityRenderer<...>) is wrong, and methods like render() cannot be found, suggesting the entire rendering API has been overhauled.
Data & NBT System: The SavedData API (used in SurvivalSaveData.java and CustomBuildingSaveData.java) has changed. Classes like SavedDataType.Builder are missing, and the getCompound method now returns an Optional<CompoundTag> instead of a direct CompoundTag.
Entity & Item API: Missing methods like hasPermissions(int) for commands, setItem(ItemStack) and shoot() for projectile items, and getYRot()/getXRot() for entities.
Type Mismatches: Incompatible type conversions are pervasive (e.g., ParticleTypes.ENTITY_EFFECT to ParticleOptions, Optional<Reference<Building>> to Building).
2. The Root Cause: Historic API Changes

As you correctly noted, Minecraft 1.21 is one of the largest technical updates ever, featuring a complete backend rewrite (the "Resource & Data Pack Overhaul") which changed countless internal APIs, class names, and method signatures. Your mod code, written for the 1.20.1 architecture, is trying to call methods and classes that no longer exist in the same form.

3. Previous Troubleshooting Context (Link 2)

The second conversation is a previous debugging session for the same mod when it was targeting 1.20.1. The assistant correctly diagnosed outdated mappings and API usage and provided specific fixes for EntityRenderer and the SavedData system for version 1.20.1.

Recommended Path Forward

Porting a complex mod to 1.21.1 is essentially a ground-up rewrite of all systems touching Minecraft's API. Here’s what you need to do:

Official Documentation is Key: Start with Mojang's and your mod loader's (Forge/NeoForge/Fabric) official 1.21.1 migration guides. These documents list every breaking change.
Update Your Foundation First: Ensure your build.gradle file is configured for 1.21.1 and the latest version of your mod loader. Regenerate your project files.
Systematic Refactoring, Not Isolated Fixes: Do not try to fix errors file-by-file. You must understand and update entire systems:

Rendering: Study how 1.21.1 entity rendering works from scratch.
Data Saving: Learn the new SavedData / PersistentState API.
Commands: Update to the new command registration API and permission checks (hasPermissions is gone).
Entities & Projectiles: The way entities are constructed, shot, and added to the world has changed.
Use Reference Code: Look at the source code of very simple mods or examples that have already been successfully ported to 1.21.1 to see the new patterns in action.
(Note: The content in the middle link about "why DeepSeek gives longer answers" is unrelated to the modding issue. It discusses the AI model's architectural differences compared to ChatGPT and Gemini.)

./gradlew clean build --refresh-dependencies
This will clean, download dependencies, compile your mod, and most importantly for us, run the necessary setup tasks. Watch the output for any errors about "decompiling" or "mapping."

🧠 Step 4: How Your Project Should Be Structured

For ForgeGradle 6.x (which you have), a correctly set up project usually has the decompiled Minecraft sources merged into your project's source sets. This means when you open your project in Cursor, you should be able to "Go to Definition" (Ctrl+Click) on a vanilla class like Entity and see its decompiled source.

Here is what a typical structure looks like after successful setup:

text
reignofnether-1.21.11-dev/
├── build.gradle                    # Targets 1.21.11
├── src/main/java/                  # YOUR mod code (with errors)
├── build/sources/main/java/        # (Sometimes) Contains merged sources
│   ├── net/minecraft/...           # Vanilla Minecraft classes
│   └── com/solegendary/...         # Your mod classes
└── .gradle/                        # Cache (don't touch)

@Override
public InteractionResult use(Level pLevel, Player pPlayer, InteractionHand pHand) {
    ItemStack itemStack = pPlayer.getItemInHand(pHand);
    // ... sound effects, item consumption logic ...

    ThrownHeroExperienceBottle bottle = new ThrownHeroExperienceBottle(pLevel, pPlayer, itemStack);

    // Set initial motion based on look vector and strength
    bottle.shoot(look.x, look.y, look.z, 1.5F, 1.0F); // Use 'shoot' method from ThrowableProjectile

    // Add to level
    pLevel.addFreshEntity(bottle);

    // Return the CORRECT interaction result for 1.21.11
    return InteractionResult.sidedSuccess(itemStack, pLevel.isClientSide());
}
